A CSS rule consists of a selector and a declaration block. The selector points to the HTML element you want to style, and the declaration block contains one or more declarations.

**Basic Syntax Structure:**
```css
selector {
  property: value;
}
```

**Example:**
```css
p {
  color: blue;
  font-size: 16px;
}
```

**Breakdown:**
- **Selector**: `p` - Selects all paragraph elements
- **Property**: `color` - The CSS property to style
- **Value**: `blue` - The value for the property
- **Declaration**: `color: blue;` - Property and value pair
- **Declaration Block**: `{ color: blue; font-size: 16px; }` - All declarations

**Multiple Declarations:**
```css
h1 {
  color: red;
  font-size: 32px;
  text-align: center;
  background-color: yellow;
}
```

**Important Rules:**
- Each declaration ends with a semicolon (;)
- Declaration blocks are surrounded by curly braces ({})
- Properties and values are separated by a colon (:)
- Multiple declarations are separated by semicolons

CSS selectors are used to select HTML elements you want to style. There are several types of selectors.

**Element Selector:**
Selects all elements with a specific tag name.
```css
p {
  color: blue;
}
```

**ID Selector:**
Selects the element with a specific id (uses #).
```css
#myHeader {
  color: red;
}
```

**Class Selector:**
Selects all elements with a specific class (uses .).
```css
.myClass {
  color: green;
}
```

**Universal Selector:**
Selects all elements (uses *).
```css
* {
  margin: 0;
  padding: 0;
}
```

**Grouping Selector:**
Selects multiple elements with the same styles.
```css
h1, h2, p {
  color: blue;
}
```

**Selector Specificity:**
- ID selectors have highest specificity
- Class selectors have medium specificity
- Element selectors have lowest specificity
- More specific selectors override less specific ones

CSS comments are used to explain your code and make it more readable. Comments are ignored by browsers.

**Syntax:**
```css
/* This is a comment */
```

**Single-line Comment:**
```css
/* This is a single-line comment */
p {
  color: blue;
}
```

**Multi-line Comment:**
```css
/*
  This is a
  multi-line comment
  It can span multiple lines
*/
h1 {
  color: red;
}
```

**Commenting Out Code:**
```css
/* p {
  color: blue;
} */
```

**Best Practices:**
- Use comments to explain complex CSS
- Comment sections of your stylesheet
- Comment out code for debugging instead of deleting
- Keep comments concise and relevant
